wikipedia_page.main: Harold Burston Peel (26 March 1900 – 1976) was an English professional footballer who played in the Football League for Bradford Park Avenue, Arsenal and Bradford City.

response: Alcock qualified as a masseur, and set up in private practice in Bradford. He was appointed trainer to his former club, Bradford City, in the 1937 close season, and was succeeded a year later by his assistant, Harry Peel. The 1939 Register finds Alcock living in Marlborough Road, Bradford, with his wife, Cora née Busfield, and working as a manipulative masseur. Cora had herself followed the same occupation before their marriage. In November 1939, he was on duty at the local first-aid station while Cora slept downstairs at home. After a spark from the fire set light to her bedding, she woke to find the room full of smoke and managed to go upstairs and rescue their baby daughter. In 1953, Alcock became masseur to Yorkshire County Cricket Club, and the club extended his services to the touring Australians for that year's Headingley Test. He later became the county's physiotherapist, and retired from the role in the 1970s.
